<br>
Much of the history isn't revealed in that manner. Isengard doesn't become a player until Two Towers, really. And you don't find out about Gandalf's struggles with Saruman at all in Fellowship, iirc.<br>
<br>
Anyways, about 2 hours into the film Two Towers, you have to realize that it's not going to end the way the book did.<br>
<br>
And yeah, as someone already pointed out, Return of the King is a much shorter book (with a large chunk of it taken up by the appendicies). So Two Towers the movie ends in a nice spot.<br>
<br>
