<br>
They've shown jack and almost NOTHING of Gondor so far.<br>
<br>
By this time in the books, the reader knows quite a bit about the kingdoms of men and Denethor and the stewardship and Aragorn's history and elendil and Arathorn.<br>
<br>
But by this point in the movie, we've only seen Minas Tirith for all of 30 seconds in the FIRST movie and it really has NO impact whatsoever with the viewers at this stage of the second movie.<br>
<br>
So taking the thing in Osgiliath from the book, and making it an actual scene in the movie that includes Frodo and Faramir, well, I just think Jackson's trying to keep Gondor a tad fresher in the viewers' minds, prepping them for the much more central role the realm is going to play in the final movie.<br>
<br>
Just my 2 cents.<br>
<br>
